      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When the moment at the fixed end of a cantilevered balcony is too high for the material to withstand, the material experiences stress. Stress is the force per unit area within materials that arises from externally applied forces, uneven heating, or permanent deformation and can cause the material to either bend or, if the stress exceeds the material's yield strength, to permanently deform or even snap.\n\nThe material at the fixed end will typically bend if the applied moment is within the elastic limit of the material. This means that the material will return to its original shape once the moment is removed. However, if the moment causes the stress to exceed the yield strength of the material, the material will undergo plastic deformation, meaning it will not return to its original shape even after the moment is removed. If the moment is extremely high and the material's tensile strength is exceeded, it could snap or fracture.\n\nEngineers calculate the safety factor for the fixed end connection by determining the maximum expected moment and dividing it by the allowable moment, which is the moment that the material can safely withstand without yielding or breaking. The safety factor is a measure of the structural capacity beyond the expected loads. It is typically expressed as a ratio or a multiple. For example, a safety factor of",
